<taxonomicName authority="Irwin &amp; Winterton, 2016" authorityName="Irwin &amp; Winterton" authorityYear="2016" class="Insecta" family="Therevidae" genus="Zelothrix" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Zelothrix warrumbungles" order="Diptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="114" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="warrumbungles">Zelothrix warrumbungles</taxonomicName>
sp. n. and 
<taxonomicName authority="Irwin &amp; Winterton, 2016" authorityName="Irwin &amp; Winterton" authorityYear="2016" class="Insecta" family="Therevidae" genus="Zelothrix" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Zelothrix yeatesi" order="Diptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="114" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="yeatesi">Zelothrix yeatesi</taxonomicName>
sp. n.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="18" lastPageNumber="115" pageId="17" pageNumber="114" type="comments">
<paragraph pageId="17" pageNumber="114">Comments.</paragraph>
<paragraph lastPageId="18" lastPageNumber="115" pageId="17" pageNumber="114">
<taxonomicName authority="Irwin &amp; Winterton, 2016" authorityName="Irwin &amp; Winterton" authorityYear="2016" class="Insecta" family="Therevidae" genus="Zelothrix" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Zelothrix" order="Diptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="114" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Zelothrix</taxonomicName>
gen. n. is a distinctive genus with a disparate distribution. Similar genera include 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Therevidae" genus="Squamopygia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Squamopygia" order="Diptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="114" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Squamopygia</taxonomicName>
<normalizedToken originalValue="KrÃ¶ber">Kroeber</normalizedToken>
, 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Therevidae" genus="Taenogerella" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Taenogerella" order="Diptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="114" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Taenogerella</taxonomicName>
Winterton &amp; Irwin and 
<taxonomicName authority="Irwin &amp; Winterton, 2016" authorityName="Irwin &amp; Winterton" authorityYear="2016" class="Insecta" family="Therevidae" genus="Sidarena" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Sidarena" order="Diptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="114" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Sidarena</taxonomicName>
gen. n. This new genus can be differentiated from 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Therevidae" genus="Squamopygia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Squamopygia" order="Diptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="114" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Squamopygia</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Irwin &amp; Winterton, 2016" authorityName="Irwin &amp; Winterton" authorityYear="2016" class="Insecta" family="Therevidae" genus="Sidarena" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Sidarena" order="Diptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="114" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Sidarena</taxonomicName>
gen. n. by the presence of two scutellar macrosetae and a medial atrium in the male gonocoxites. The wing is extensively patterned in 
<taxonomicName authority="Irwin &amp; Winterton, 2016" authorityName="Irwin &amp; Winterton" authorityYear="2016" class="Insecta" family="Therevidae" genus="Zelothrix" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Zelothrix" order="Diptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="114" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Zelothrix</taxonomicName>
gen. n. but not banded as in 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Therevidae" genus="Squamopygia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Squamopygia" order="Diptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="114" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Squamopygia</taxonomicName>
. 
<taxonomicName authority="Irwin &amp; Winterton, 2016" authorityName="Irwin &amp; Winterton" authorityYear="2016" class="Insecta" family="Therevidae" genus="Zelothrix" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Zelothrix" order="Diptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="114" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Zelothrix</taxonomicName>
gen. n. is separable from 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Therevidae" genus="Taenogerella" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Taenogerella" order="Diptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="114" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Taenogerella</taxonomicName>
by the latter having a downward directed distiphallus in the male genitalia and three spermathecae (two 
<pageBreakToken pageId="18" pageNumber="115" start="start">in</pageBreakToken>
<taxonomicName authority="Irwin &amp; Winterton, 2016" authorityName="Irwin &amp; Winterton" authorityYear="2016" class="Insecta" family="Therevidae" genus="Zelothrix" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Zelothrix" order="Diptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="115" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Zelothrix</taxonomicName>
gen. n.). A significant departure from the female genitalic complement of three spermathecae typically found in 
<taxonomicName lsidName="" pageId="18" pageNumber="115" rank="subfamily" subfamily="Agapophytinae">Agapophytinae</taxonomicName>
, is that 
<taxonomicName authority="Irwin &amp; Winterton, 2016" authorityName="Irwin &amp; Winterton" authorityYear="2016" class="Insecta" family="Therevidae" genus="Zelothrix" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Zelothrix" order="Diptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="115" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Zelothrix</taxonomicName>
gen. n. only has two spermathecae, a condition found in 
<taxonomicName lsidName="" pageId="18" pageNumber="115" rank="subfamily" subfamily="Therevinae">Therevinae</taxonomicName>
. No other genus of 
<taxonomicName lsidName="" pageId="18" pageNumber="115" rank="subfamily" subfamily="Agapophytinae">Agapophytinae</taxonomicName>
has two spermathecae, although the distantly related agapophytine genus 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Therevidae" genus="Bonjeania" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Bonjeania" order="Diptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="115" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Bonjeania</taxonomicName>
Winterton &amp; Skevington has only a single spermatheca (
<bibRefCitation author="Winterton, SL" journalOrPublisher="Systematic Entomology" pageId="24" pageNumber="121" pagination="295 - 324" title="Phylogenetic revision of Bonjeania Irwin &amp; Lyneborg (Diptera: Therevidae)." url="10.1046/j.1365-3113.2000.00107.x" volume="25" year="2000">Winterton et al. 2000</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="18" pageNumber="115">
<taxonomicName authority="Irwin &amp; Winterton, 2016" authorityName="Irwin &amp; Winterton" authorityYear="2016" class="Insecta" family="Therevidae" genus="Zelothrix" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Zelothrix warrumbungles" order="Diptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="115" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="warrumbungles">Zelothrix warrumbungles</taxonomicName>
sp. n. is a locally highly abundant species found mainly in Warrumbungle National Park (New South Wales) (Fig. 4), while 
<taxonomicName authority="Irwin &amp; Winterton, 2016" authorityName="Irwin &amp; Winterton" authorityYear="2016" class="Insecta" family="Therevidae" genus="Zelothrix" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Zelothrix yeatesi" order="Diptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="115" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="yeatesi">Zelothrix yeatesi</taxonomicName>
sp. n. is a rarely collected species endemic to Porongurup National Park (Western Australia). The two species are very similar in appearance.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="18" pageNumber="115" type="etymology">
<paragraph pageId="18" pageNumber="115">Etymology.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="18" pageNumber="115">
This name is derived from the Greek, 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Zelosâ">Zelos-</normalizedToken>
emulation, and 
<normalizedToken originalValue="thrixâ">thrix-</normalizedToken>
